WEBVTT

00:01.335 --> 00:03.337
[metal clangs]

00:05.881 --> 00:08.884
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:08.884 --> 00:15.474
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:15.474 --> 00:17.643
<i>- I'm Mike Rowley.</i>
<i>I'm a teacher,</i>

00:17.643 --> 00:21.522
and a coach--7th and 8th grade
girls basketball.

00:21.522 --> 00:23.941
<i>I am very competitive,</i>
<i>and I figure</i>

00:23.941 --> 00:26.276
<i>if I just beat</i>
<i>one person per round,</i>

00:26.276 --> 00:27.778
I can win.

00:27.778 --> 00:28.987
<i>- My name is Cody Craig.</i>

00:28.987 --> 00:30.322
<i>Some people have been blessed</i>

00:30.322 --> 00:31.907
with a silver tongue.
I have not,

00:31.907 --> 00:33.200
but I have been blessed
with silver balls 'cause

00:33.200 --> 00:34.701
I can make a lot of things

00:34.701 --> 00:36.370
<i>and I have such</i>
<i>a diverse background</i>

00:36.370 --> 00:37.663
that could really give
me an edge.

00:37.663 --> 00:39.164
<i>- My name is Rob Sign.</i>

00:39.164 --> 00:40.916
I watched "Forged In Fire"
and said,

00:40.916 --> 00:43.585
"I have to do that."
and now I'm on it. [laughs]

00:43.585 --> 00:45.295
<i>Newly married,</i>
<i>my wife is awesome.</i>

00:45.295 --> 00:46.880
<i>She supports my blademaking.</i>

00:46.880 --> 00:49.341
Hasn't been a hindrance
to me at all.

00:49.341 --> 00:51.176
Cut that out.
[laughs]

00:51.176 --> 00:53.345
<i>I told her</i>
<i>I would embarrass her.</i>

00:53.345 --> 00:54.763
<i>- My name is Buddy Thomas</i>

00:54.763 --> 00:56.640
and I want to become

00:56.640 --> 00:58.141
the first deaf

00:58.141 --> 01:00.269
"Forged in Fire" champion.

01:00.269 --> 01:01.895
I wanna be out here

01:01.895 --> 01:03.522
to represent the deaf community

01:03.522 --> 01:06.233
and to show 'em that
anything is possible.

01:06.233 --> 01:07.693
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:07.693 --> 01:10.320
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

01:10.320 --> 01:11.989
You are here for
three timed rounds

01:11.989 --> 01:13.615
of edged weapon making
competition

01:13.615 --> 01:15.826
designed to test every aspect
of your skills

01:15.826 --> 01:18.120
in front of
a panel of expert judges.

01:18.120 --> 01:19.621
Let's meet them now.

01:19.621 --> 01:23.250
Two-time "Forged In Fire"
Champion, Ben Abbott.

01:23.250 --> 01:26.712
Historic weapons recreation
specialist, David Baker.

01:26.712 --> 01:29.506
And last, edged weapons
specialist, Doug Marcaida.

01:29.506 --> 01:30.966
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:30.966 --> 01:33.510
Gentlemen,
to win this competition

01:33.510 --> 01:37.598
You need skill, determination,
and drive.

01:37.598 --> 01:39.933
You don't need much else,
other than

01:39.933 --> 01:41.768
what's underneath the cloth.

01:41.768 --> 01:43.020
Go ahead and lift that up.

01:43.020 --> 01:45.147
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:45.147 --> 01:46.273
Open the can.

01:46.273 --> 01:52.154
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:52.154 --> 01:53.655
We're calling this one

01:53.655 --> 01:55.532
"Blade in a Can."

01:55.532 --> 01:57.200
<i>You will combine</i>
<i>that steel wool</i>

01:57.200 --> 02:00.037
<i>with 1095 powder</i>
<i>in a canister</i>

02:00.037 --> 02:01.621
<i>to make a Damascus billet.</i>

02:01.621 --> 02:04.041
<i>from which to forge</i>
<i>your blades.</i>

02:04.041 --> 02:05.959
<i>- I was hoping for a car.</i>

02:05.959 --> 02:07.836
I have no idea

02:07.836 --> 02:09.713
what I'm gonna do
with this now.

02:09.713 --> 02:13.008
- You'll be forging
gut hook knives.

02:13.008 --> 02:14.843
They're not just good
for hunting,

02:14.843 --> 02:16.970
but also for skinning,
building,

02:16.970 --> 02:18.722
and survival purposes.

02:18.722 --> 02:21.266
Your blade parameters
are as follows;

02:21.266 --> 02:23.685
<i>the length of your blade</i>
<i>must be between</i>

02:23.685 --> 02:25.103
<i>8 and 10 inches,</i>

02:25.103 --> 02:26.605
<i>the overall length</i>
<i>of your weapon</i>

02:26.605 --> 02:28.357
<i>must not exceed 22 inches,</i>

02:28.357 --> 02:30.734
<i>and you must include</i>
<i>a sharpened gut hook</i>

02:30.734 --> 02:32.152
<i>somewhere near the tip.</i>

02:32.152 --> 02:34.196
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:34.196 --> 02:35.781
Keep in mind that in
the second round

02:35.781 --> 02:37.741
you'll be attaching handles
to those blades

02:37.741 --> 02:40.661
to turn them into fully
functional hunting knives

02:40.661 --> 02:42.621
that will be tested
for strength

02:42.621 --> 02:45.415
and durability in a bone chop,

02:45.415 --> 02:47.042
and for edge retention

02:47.042 --> 02:50.170
in a pork shoulder slice.

02:50.170 --> 02:53.131
You will have three hours
in which to forge your blades.

02:53.131 --> 02:54.257
You ready?

02:54.257 --> 02:55.926
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:55.926 --> 02:57.511
Good luck, bladesmiths,

02:57.511 --> 02:59.638
your three hours starts...

02:59.638 --> 03:00.597
now.

03:00.597 --> 03:03.392
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:03.392 --> 03:05.352
The first thing
that these guys need to do

03:05.352 --> 03:06.603
is start setting up

03:06.603 --> 03:08.438
these canisters right?
- Yup.

03:08.438 --> 03:10.357
- Challenge is to get
the 1095 powder

03:10.357 --> 03:12.693
in and around all
of the steel wool.

03:12.693 --> 03:14.403
- You gotta really pack that in

03:14.403 --> 03:16.238
because if not, you're gonna
have a lot of space

03:16.238 --> 03:17.489
in there for pockets

03:17.489 --> 03:19.408
to create a lot of
delaminations.

03:19.408 --> 03:22.285
- I've never made a knife out
of steel wool before.

03:22.285 --> 03:23.995
Who thinks of this stuff?

03:23.995 --> 03:25.330
<i>The can is mild steel,</i>

03:25.330 --> 03:27.207
you don't want
that on your knife.

03:27.207 --> 03:29.251
<i>I put white-out in there</i>
<i>because the zinc</i>

03:29.251 --> 03:32.045
<i>in the white-out keeps</i>
<i>the mild steel canister</i>

03:32.045 --> 03:34.965
from welding to
the high carbon steel.

03:34.965 --> 03:36.508
There we go.

03:36.508 --> 03:38.135
<i>I'm worried about</i>
<i>the steel wool</i>

03:38.135 --> 03:41.012
'cause it's all fluffy
and how do you make sure

03:41.012 --> 03:43.390
that there are no air pockets
in it?

03:43.390 --> 03:45.225
- So these steel wool pads,

03:45.225 --> 03:47.227
they don't have
a lot of density.

03:47.227 --> 03:48.812
- That's why you gotta
put the powder in

03:48.812 --> 03:51.106
and you really wanna be
compressing that stuff down,

03:51.106 --> 03:52.607
making it as dense as possible.

03:52.607 --> 03:54.526
- If that canister's not packed

03:54.526 --> 03:56.695
when you open it up
you might have a pile of dust.

03:56.695 --> 03:59.406
- That means it didn't
weld in there.

03:59.406 --> 04:00.824
- Definitely hot.

04:00.824 --> 04:02.659
Like, you could bake a turkey
right there.

04:02.659 --> 04:04.411
Be all crisped up in an hour

04:04.411 --> 04:05.871
just like grandma used to make.

04:05.871 --> 04:07.998
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:07.998 --> 04:10.333
<i>- With canister Damascus</i>
<i>I know the theories,</i>

04:10.333 --> 04:12.252
but I have zero practical
experience

04:12.252 --> 04:13.837
on how to actually do it.

04:13.837 --> 04:15.797
<i>So just getting</i>
<i>a usable billet of steel</i>

04:15.797 --> 04:18.758
will be interesting
in and of itself.

04:18.758 --> 04:20.760
- Cody has just gone straight
to, like,

04:20.760 --> 04:22.763
adding the 1095 powder

04:22.763 --> 04:24.514
to the steel wool itself,

04:24.514 --> 04:25.974
no liquid paper.

04:25.974 --> 04:28.143
- Well, you're gonna be
forging to shape

04:28.143 --> 04:30.687
a lot sooner without having
to remove that can.

04:30.687 --> 04:33.148
<i>- I have about seven pieces</i>
<i>of steel wool in my canister</i>

04:33.148 --> 04:35.275
<i>and I'm sifting down powder</i>
<i>as I pack 'em in</i>

04:35.275 --> 04:37.903
so hopefully it'll be
a very good, usable billet.

04:37.903 --> 04:40.405
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:40.405 --> 04:43.033
- Rob's already over
at the welder.

04:43.033 --> 04:44.785
- Steel wool is nice
'cause it does have

04:44.785 --> 04:46.453
a lot of carbon in it.
It shows in how

04:46.453 --> 04:47.871
<i>it lights on fire</i>
<i>when you use it</i>

04:47.871 --> 04:49.372
<i>in survival kits and stuff.</i>

04:49.372 --> 04:50.874
<i>But all the air</i>
<i>in those gaps,</i>

04:50.874 --> 04:52.375
<i>if they don't get filled</i>

04:52.375 --> 04:54.127
in a forge weld it'll--
it'll just fall apart

04:54.127 --> 04:55.337
it won't forge weld to itself.

04:55.337 --> 04:57.297
Now that's more like it.

04:57.297 --> 04:58.924
<i>I leave a vent in my can</i>

04:58.924 --> 05:00.717
to make sure all
the gasses in the can

05:00.717 --> 05:03.261
have a vent so when I press it

05:03.261 --> 05:04.888
it doesn't explode.

05:04.888 --> 05:06.139
[groans]

05:06.139 --> 05:07.808
Nah, we're losing too much.

05:07.808 --> 05:09.559
- Dude, there are sparks flying
out of that forge

05:09.559 --> 05:11.186
like somebody's in there
with a grinder.

05:11.186 --> 05:13.146
- I know I've got too big
a vent hole in it.

05:13.146 --> 05:14.564
<i>Which means that</i>
<i>my powdered steel's escaping</i>

05:14.564 --> 05:15.816
<i>and oxygen is getting in.</i>

05:15.816 --> 05:16.900
So everything's
getting oxidized

05:16.900 --> 05:18.485
and it won't weld together.

05:18.485 --> 05:20.153
<i>Went and welded it</i>
<i>a little bit more</i>

05:20.153 --> 05:21.696
<i>where I thought it was</i>
<i>too big of a hole.</i>

05:21.696 --> 05:23.281
So I think that definitely
sealed it up,

05:23.281 --> 05:24.574
so it's not gonna
lose anything.

05:24.574 --> 05:25.659
It's not gonna oxidize inside

05:25.659 --> 05:26.785
to stop it from forge welding.

05:26.785 --> 05:28.370
<i>As of now we're just</i>

05:28.370 --> 05:29.913
<i>letting it heat up</i>
<i>to forge weld.</i>

05:29.913 --> 05:31.498
Come on, baby, heat up for me.

05:31.498 --> 05:35.210
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:35.210 --> 05:38.129
- Buddy only has 15%
of his hearing,

05:38.129 --> 05:40.841
so he'll have
an interpreter on set

05:40.841 --> 05:42.634
for the entire time.

05:42.634 --> 05:45.011
- I don't want to over pack

05:45.011 --> 05:48.098
<i>the canister on the press.</i>

05:48.098 --> 05:51.226
<i>If I do then there's</i>
<i>more of a chance</i>

05:51.226 --> 05:52.978
that the canister's gonna weld

05:52.978 --> 05:55.730
and that's gonna bypass
the liquid paper.

05:55.730 --> 05:58.942
<i>I don't want the canister</i>
<i>to attach to the billet.</i>

05:58.942 --> 06:00.443
- It looks to me like Buddy

06:00.443 --> 06:01.736
really jumped the gun.

06:01.736 --> 06:03.154
I don't think he had
that canister

06:03.154 --> 06:05.031
in the forge nearly long enough

06:05.031 --> 06:06.283
to get the center
of that heated up

06:06.283 --> 06:08.201
to where it needs to weld.

06:08.201 --> 06:10.662
- Bladesmiths,
there's only two hours

06:10.662 --> 06:12.539
remaining in this round!

06:12.539 --> 06:14.291
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:14.291 --> 06:16.251
Mike still has to peel

06:16.251 --> 06:18.879
the can off of that billet.
- Yeah.

06:18.879 --> 06:21.423
- It's very thin
and it looks solid to me.

06:21.423 --> 06:23.383
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:23.383 --> 06:25.594
- It is brutally difficult

06:25.594 --> 06:27.387
to get that can off.

06:27.387 --> 06:30.307
That thing is on there
all the way.

06:30.307 --> 06:33.602
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:33.602 --> 06:35.061
There we go.

06:35.061 --> 06:37.814
<i>I finally get the sides</i>
<i>cut off,</i>

06:37.814 --> 06:39.858
and I notice that there's
a couple places

06:39.858 --> 06:42.027
where the steel had folded
in the mild steel.

06:42.027 --> 06:44.112
So I feel, like,
I've got enough steel left

06:44.112 --> 06:46.573
that I can grind
those little issues out.

06:46.573 --> 06:49.659
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:49.659 --> 06:51.328
<i>- Now it's time to take this</i>
<i>outer shell off.</i>

06:51.328 --> 06:53.496
I'm just hoping I've pressed
it enough,

06:53.496 --> 06:55.040
and heated it up enough
to where

06:55.040 --> 06:56.916
the forge welds are holding.

06:56.916 --> 06:59.836
- Cody is trying to peel
the can off of a blade

06:59.836 --> 07:01.630
that used zero white-out.

07:01.630 --> 07:03.340
- What Cody is doing right now

07:03.340 --> 07:05.467
is completely worthless.

07:05.467 --> 07:07.135
The can is part of that steel.

07:07.135 --> 07:10.305
That's one solid piece
of steel.

07:10.305 --> 07:11.973
- Process of taking
this canister off

07:11.973 --> 07:14.059
is not going
how I wanted it to.

07:14.059 --> 07:16.394
I'm just kind of confused
as to my next step on this

07:16.394 --> 07:17.854
and what I'm gonna do.

07:17.854 --> 07:19.773
- Maybe he's gonna butterfly
his blade.

07:19.773 --> 07:21.274
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:21.274 --> 07:22.609
- I'm gonna turn this thing
inside out

07:22.609 --> 07:23.693
basically by cutting off

07:23.693 --> 07:25.028
the one piece of mild steel

07:25.028 --> 07:26.363
<i>that I can get off of it,</i>

07:26.363 --> 07:27.739
<i>flattening it back out</i>

07:27.739 --> 07:28.948
<i>and almost kind of</i>
<i>filleting it</i>

07:28.948 --> 07:30.408
like a chicken breast,

07:30.408 --> 07:32.118
<i>and then folding it back</i>
<i>in on itself</i>

07:32.118 --> 07:34.079
<i>so I can get that 1095</i>
<i>on the outside.</i>

07:34.079 --> 07:35.413
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:35.413 --> 07:37.582
And I will forge weld it
back together.

07:37.582 --> 07:40.043
- Cody's killing himself
right now.

07:40.043 --> 07:42.921
- Cody's creating ways
to work harder.

07:42.921 --> 07:44.798
<i>- My plan B is</i>
<i>definitely risky.</i>

07:44.798 --> 07:46.049
Cross my fingers
that it'll pay off.

07:46.049 --> 07:49.177
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:49.177 --> 07:50.845
- Rob's got one of his corners

07:50.845 --> 07:52.514
peeled off right now.

07:52.514 --> 07:54.891
<i>- I look inside</i>
<i>and it lights on fire.</i>

07:54.891 --> 07:56.393
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:56.393 --> 07:58.853
- That's probably uncooked
steel wool.

07:58.853 --> 08:00.063
- Oh, no, that's very bad.
It means that there

08:00.063 --> 08:01.272
was oxygen in the can.

08:01.272 --> 08:02.273
- It's gonna crumble.

08:02.273 --> 08:03.316
- Yep. That's the end of that.

08:03.316 --> 08:05.068
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:05.068 --> 08:07.237
- I looked at it and I went,
"Nope, this is done."

08:07.237 --> 08:09.823
- Rob has actually started
on his second billet.

08:09.823 --> 08:12.575
- I know that
I'm on a time crunch now.

08:12.575 --> 08:14.577
<i>I thought making a canister</i>

08:14.577 --> 08:16.496
<i>of Damascus with steel wool</i>
<i>in three hours</i>

08:16.496 --> 08:19.082
was gonna be tough.
But doing it in under two?

08:19.082 --> 08:22.085
I am worried I'm not even gonna
get to turn in a blade.

08:22.085 --> 08:23.545
[sighs]

08:23.545 --> 08:26.589
- Bladesmiths,
you have just 90 minutes

08:26.589 --> 08:28.425
remaining to finish your work!

08:28.425 --> 08:30.093
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:30.093 --> 08:32.554
- This is a big reveal moment
for Buddy

08:32.554 --> 08:35.598
as he chisels into his billet.

08:35.598 --> 08:38.226
- When I get ready to pry off
the canister

08:38.226 --> 08:39.686
<i>I'm nervous.</i>

08:39.686 --> 08:41.312
- Moment of truth
right here.

08:41.312 --> 08:42.605
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:42.605 --> 08:44.232
- Yeah.
- Oh, boy.

08:44.232 --> 08:45.817
- There's a lot of sparks
coming out

08:45.817 --> 08:47.569
of Buddy's billet there.

08:47.569 --> 08:49.654
That's not what
you want to see.

08:49.654 --> 08:52.157
This is unwelded powder.

08:52.157 --> 08:54.993
- This is getting frustrating.

08:54.993 --> 08:56.703
- Oh, and it just
broke in half.

08:56.703 --> 08:58.663
- There goes half of it.
- We can see a piece

08:58.663 --> 09:00.582
of it stayed inside of there.

09:00.582 --> 09:02.667
- Oh, man.

09:02.667 --> 09:04.252
<i>I don't know where it's gonna</i>
<i>go from here.</i>

09:04.252 --> 09:04.878
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:07.630 --> 09:08.882
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:08.882 --> 09:10.675
- Oh, and it just
broke in half.

09:10.675 --> 09:11.968
- There goes half of it.
- We can see a piece

09:11.968 --> 09:13.344
of it stayed inside of there.

09:13.344 --> 09:15.138
<i>- I see the steel wool</i>

09:15.138 --> 09:17.432
peeking out from
the inside of it.

09:17.432 --> 09:19.184
Oh, man.

09:19.184 --> 09:20.769
- It's just really porous
right now.

09:20.769 --> 09:22.187
he just didn't spend
the amount of time

09:22.187 --> 09:24.189
he needed to compacting
that billet.

09:24.189 --> 09:25.565
- So brittle!

09:25.565 --> 09:28.318
So fine.

09:28.318 --> 09:29.944
At this point I'm thinking,

09:29.944 --> 09:32.489
"Am I going to abandon this

09:32.489 --> 09:35.200
and start a new canister?"

09:35.200 --> 09:36.743
- There's enough steel
in that block

09:36.743 --> 09:38.870
that fell to the ground
to make a knife out of.

09:38.870 --> 09:41.748
- I have 75%
of my original billet.

09:41.748 --> 09:44.209
<i>I'm gonna go ahead</i>
<i>and try to work with it.</i>

09:44.209 --> 09:46.836
- One hour remaining,
bladesmiths!

09:46.836 --> 09:48.713
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:48.713 --> 09:51.091
- Come on, you rowdy devil.

09:51.091 --> 09:53.259
I try to make it easy on myself

09:53.259 --> 09:55.136
by hot cutting the gut hook in.

09:55.136 --> 09:58.431
<i>because the steel</i>
<i>is so malleable.</i>

09:58.431 --> 10:00.100
- So the idea with a gut hook

10:00.100 --> 10:02.143
is that when you're gutting
your game

10:02.143 --> 10:05.105
you don't perforate the bowel
and taint the meat.

10:05.105 --> 10:06.898
- Because you don't have
a slicing motion,

10:06.898 --> 10:08.316
it has to be very sharp.
- Okay.

10:08.316 --> 10:10.110
- Just to split things
wide open.

10:10.110 --> 10:12.445
- The only issue with putting
a gut hook into a knife,

10:12.445 --> 10:15.615
I think, is just that it
weakens that one spot.

10:15.615 --> 10:18.368
<i>And so you need</i>
<i>to have enough thickness</i>

10:18.368 --> 10:20.453
and enough depth
that it doesn't affect

10:20.453 --> 10:22.789
the rest of the knife.

10:22.789 --> 10:23.957
There we go.

10:23.957 --> 10:27.127
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:27.127 --> 10:28.378
- Look at Cody's blade.

10:28.378 --> 10:30.880
It's coming along.
- It's come back.

10:30.880 --> 10:32.966
<i>- I'm very happy with</i>
<i>that secondary forge weld.</i>

10:32.966 --> 10:35.552
I think I successfully got
the 1095 on the outside

10:35.552 --> 10:38.304
and can actually begin
shaping my knife.

10:38.304 --> 10:40.765
I have put a few gut hooks on
things in the past.

10:40.765 --> 10:43.268
<i>I've always found it</i>
<i>very easy to do that.</i>

10:43.268 --> 10:45.019
- Now it looks like Cody
over here

10:45.019 --> 10:46.479
is actually forging

10:46.479 --> 10:48.815
his hook into his blade.
What do you think?

10:48.815 --> 10:50.233
- I'd probably just
grind it in.

10:50.233 --> 10:52.026
If you look at
the back of a blade

10:52.026 --> 10:55.446
and you chisel it,
it moves metal up and out.

10:55.446 --> 10:57.115
And this is supposed
to sort of be

10:57.115 --> 10:59.159
in line with the rest
of the back.

10:59.159 --> 11:04.831
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:04.831 --> 11:06.875
- Buddy's blade,
the more he forges it,

11:06.875 --> 11:08.376
the more it thins out.

11:08.376 --> 11:09.919
- I'm pretty confident

11:09.919 --> 11:11.588
that I'm gonna meet
the parameters.

11:11.588 --> 11:13.590
<i>I gotta get</i>
<i>that gut hook done.</i>

11:13.590 --> 11:15.675
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:15.675 --> 11:17.135
<i>But I gotta be careful</i>

11:17.135 --> 11:19.262
not to lose
my blade parameters.

11:19.262 --> 11:21.014
- One thing I love about
what Buddy's doing

11:21.014 --> 11:22.265
is he's not giving up.

11:22.265 --> 11:26.227
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:26.227 --> 11:28.479
- The second canister's going
a lot better than the first.

11:28.479 --> 11:30.356
<i>I decide I want to grind</i>
<i>this whole can off</i>

11:30.356 --> 11:33.526
so I can start shaping
my knife.

11:33.526 --> 11:35.486
- I'm happy to see Rob
on the grinder,

11:35.486 --> 11:37.322
especially after
he started over.

11:37.322 --> 11:39.782
- ♪ I'm a madman with
the grinder ♪

11:39.782 --> 11:41.326
- Once he got off the forge

11:41.326 --> 11:42.869
and right into the grinder,

11:42.869 --> 11:44.370
you're starting to see
good shape to it.

11:44.370 --> 11:45.914
<i>- Just gotta get it</i>
<i>profiled up,</i>

11:45.914 --> 11:47.165
get that gut hook in there
real quick,

11:47.165 --> 11:48.333
and I gotta get the heat treat.

11:48.333 --> 11:50.376
Come on, cut.

11:50.376 --> 11:54.380
- 20 minutes, bladesmiths!

11:54.380 --> 11:56.883
All right, so Mike
just quenched his blade.

11:56.883 --> 11:58.968
- There's flames
and it's glorious

11:58.968 --> 12:01.012
<i>and the gods of knifemaking</i>

12:01.012 --> 12:02.805
<i>are cheering and celebrating.</i>

12:02.805 --> 12:04.807
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:04.807 --> 12:07.185
And then I look at it
and I notice there's a warp.

12:07.185 --> 12:08.519
Hoo, baby.

12:08.519 --> 12:10.271
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:10.271 --> 12:12.398
<i>I go right straight</i>
<i>to the vise</i>

12:12.398 --> 12:14.525
and try to start straightening
that blade.

12:14.525 --> 12:19.280
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:19.280 --> 12:21.741
- Cody just quenched.

12:21.741 --> 12:23.743
<i>- I don't really see</i>
<i>any warps.</i>

12:23.743 --> 12:25.995
<i>I gotta test the file.</i>

12:25.995 --> 12:29.332
And it does skate across
that edge so I'm happy.

12:29.332 --> 12:31.334
<i>Now I'm gonna go true it up</i>
<i>on the grinder.</i>

12:31.334 --> 12:36.756
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:36.756 --> 12:39.008
<i>- My biggest concern is</i>

12:39.008 --> 12:40.843
I don't want to burn
that tip off.

12:40.843 --> 12:43.721
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:43.721 --> 12:45.014
- Buddy just quenched.

12:45.014 --> 12:49.269
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:49.269 --> 12:51.437
- No warp.

12:51.437 --> 12:53.898
I'm happy about this.

12:53.898 --> 12:55.900
<i>I feel like I completed</i>
<i>my blade.</i>

12:55.900 --> 12:58.444
<i>I feel like</i>
<i>I met my parameter.</i>

12:58.444 --> 13:01.614
- Buddy's blade is looking
really lean.

13:01.614 --> 13:03.157
He worked really hard
to draw it out to length.

13:03.157 --> 13:04.534
He measured it several times.

13:04.534 --> 13:06.244
Hoping he's there.
- Yeah, me too.

13:06.244 --> 13:09.622
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:09.622 --> 13:11.791
- Rob is the only one who
hasn't quenched yet.

13:11.791 --> 13:13.209
<i>- Come on, come on,</i>
<i>I'm looking at the clock,</i>

13:13.209 --> 13:14.627
like, man,
I know I got to quench this,

13:14.627 --> 13:15.878
make sure it's hard.

13:15.878 --> 13:18.047
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:18.047 --> 13:19.924
all: Oh!

13:19.924 --> 13:21.217
- Whoo-hoo!

13:21.217 --> 13:22.385
- Did you scorch
your eyebrows off?

13:22.385 --> 13:24.512
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:24.512 --> 13:25.972
- Please let this blade
be hard.

13:25.972 --> 13:27.932
[metal scraping]

13:27.932 --> 13:30.351
Oh, hell yeah.

13:30.351 --> 13:33.354
- Five, four, three

13:33.354 --> 13:35.398
two, one.

13:35.398 --> 13:37.108
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines

13:37.108 --> 13:38.693
drop your tools!
This first round

13:38.693 --> 13:41.821
of bladesmithing competition
is over!

13:41.821 --> 13:43.531
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:43.531 --> 13:45.742
- This was the toughest
challenge I've ever faced

13:45.742 --> 13:47.577
working in a forge.

13:47.577 --> 13:49.495
<i>And I'm looking forward to</i>

13:49.495 --> 13:52.790
hopefully making it past
the first round.

13:52.790 --> 13:54.375
- All right, bladesmiths,

13:54.375 --> 13:55.543
now it's time for the judges

13:55.543 --> 13:57.837
to take a closer look
at your work.

13:57.837 --> 13:59.505
Mike, you're up first.

13:59.505 --> 14:01.924
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:01.924 --> 14:03.593
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:03.593 --> 14:05.011
<i>- Well, Mike,</i>
<i>I like the profile</i>

14:05.011 --> 14:06.262
<i>of your knife here.</i>

14:06.262 --> 14:08.556
The gut hook is
a little aggressive.

14:08.556 --> 14:10.099
It's gonna need
a lot of refinement.

14:10.099 --> 14:11.642
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:11.642 --> 14:13.978
There is a bit of a warp here,
Mike,

14:13.978 --> 14:16.939
But, all in all, well done.
- Thank you.

14:16.939 --> 14:19.150
- Cody, you're up next.

14:19.150 --> 14:20.443
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:20.443 --> 14:22.278
<i>- That's a nasty gut hook.</i>

14:22.278 --> 14:24.739
Shaped properly
it'll work pretty good.

14:24.739 --> 14:26.407
Shaped improperly

14:26.407 --> 14:28.451
it just pulls the knife
way down into the gut,

14:28.451 --> 14:30.787
and that becomes a problem.

14:30.787 --> 14:33.081
You got a crack right here.

14:33.081 --> 14:34.791
Leaving that there,
it's a stress riser.

14:34.791 --> 14:36.667
Any stress in that blade is
just gonna shoot it

14:36.667 --> 14:38.669
right up through there.
- Okay.

14:38.669 --> 14:40.171
- Rob, you're up next.

14:40.171 --> 14:41.756
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:41.756 --> 14:43.674
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:43.674 --> 14:45.676
- All right, Rob.
Good job on knowing

14:45.676 --> 14:47.470
and starting over and fresh.

14:47.470 --> 14:49.806
Your gut hook definitely needs
to be refined.

14:49.806 --> 14:51.432
Overall, it looks solid.

14:51.432 --> 14:53.184
Good job.
- Thank you.

14:53.184 --> 14:55.019
- All right, Buddy.
Please present your blade

14:55.019 --> 14:56.354
to the judges.

14:56.354 --> 14:57.897
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:57.897 --> 15:00.024
<i>- Well, Buddy, unfortunately</i>

15:00.024 --> 15:01.776
I don't think you compacted

15:01.776 --> 15:03.861
the can enough
in the beginning,

15:03.861 --> 15:07.490
and you have a lot of cracking
on the blade.

15:07.490 --> 15:09.283
I really applaud
that this is here

15:09.283 --> 15:12.161
because a lot of other smiths
would have just given up.

15:12.161 --> 15:13.579
Well done.

15:13.579 --> 15:15.164
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:15.164 --> 15:17.125
- Bladesmiths,
the judges have completed

15:17.125 --> 15:18.626
their deliberation.

15:18.626 --> 15:20.670
It's time for one of you
to leave The Forge.

15:20.670 --> 15:25.675
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:25.675 --> 15:27.051
Buddy,

15:27.051 --> 15:29.470
your blade didn't make the cut.

15:29.470 --> 15:31.305
- Well, Buddy,
you fought really hard

15:31.305 --> 15:33.015
out there
and I know that we all

15:33.015 --> 15:34.642
respect you very much
for your efforts.

15:34.642 --> 15:36.144
But at the end of the day

15:36.144 --> 15:38.229
there just isn't enough
material left

15:38.229 --> 15:40.773
in your knife to fix the issues
that we saw,

15:40.773 --> 15:43.025
and that's why we're sending
you home.

15:43.025 --> 15:45.278
- Buddy, please surrender
your blade.

15:45.278 --> 15:46.696
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:46.696 --> 15:47.738
<i>- You know, I came out here</i>

15:47.738 --> 15:49.532
to prove that I could do it

15:49.532 --> 15:51.617
<i>and I didn't give up.</i>

15:51.617 --> 15:54.162
<i>And I'm proud that</i>
<i>I was able to present</i>

15:54.162 --> 15:57.039
a full knife to the judges.

15:57.039 --> 15:59.417
Thank you, guys,
for having me here

15:59.417 --> 16:02.837
and love you all
and keep on smiling.

16:02.837 --> 16:06.215
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:06.215 --> 16:07.675
- All right, bladesmiths.

16:07.675 --> 16:09.510
Good job.
You made it to round two.

16:09.510 --> 16:11.262
But now that those blades have
been tempered

16:11.262 --> 16:13.389
it's time to turn them
into fully functional

16:13.389 --> 16:15.892
gut hook knives by attaching
handles to them.

16:15.892 --> 16:17.768
Seeing how these
are hunting knives,

16:17.768 --> 16:20.396
we would you like to use
only natural materials

16:20.396 --> 16:21.981
to craft those handles.

16:21.981 --> 16:24.317
You'll have three hours
in this round.

16:24.317 --> 16:27.153
After the time runs out
we'll be testing them

16:27.153 --> 16:29.697
for strength and durability
in a bone chop,

16:29.697 --> 16:33.534
and for edge retention
in a pork shoulder slice.

16:33.534 --> 16:34.744
Good luck, bladesmiths.

16:34.744 --> 16:36.996
Your three hours starts now.

16:36.996 --> 16:38.539
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:38.539 --> 16:40.666
All right, we've got some
blades out there

16:40.666 --> 16:44.378
with serious structural issues.
- Yeah.

16:44.378 --> 16:47.089
<i>- The warp of the blade is</i>
<i>the most pressing concern.</i>

16:47.089 --> 16:49.675
If it doesn't straighten,
you're in trouble.

16:49.675 --> 16:51.677
<i>I'm gonna use</i>
<i>a three-pin technique</i>

16:51.677 --> 16:53.763
<i>to address any</i>
<i>of those issues.</i>

16:53.763 --> 16:55.431
<i>Heat up the back just</i>
<i>a little bit,</i>

16:55.431 --> 16:57.683
<i>soften it, get it to</i>
<i>a nice blue color.</i>

16:57.683 --> 16:59.143
- The biggest danger

16:59.143 --> 17:00.937
is always having
that heat travel

17:00.937 --> 17:02.772
into the blade itself
and losing the temper

17:02.772 --> 17:04.649
on the edge.
- Okay.

17:04.649 --> 17:06.150
<i>- If I tighten it down</i>
<i>too much</i>

17:06.150 --> 17:07.818
and it breaks, I'm done.

17:07.818 --> 17:09.904
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:09.904 --> 17:12.031
<i>- The crack is definitely</i>
<i>the biggest priority.</i>

17:12.031 --> 17:13.950
I want to see
if I can grind it out.

17:13.950 --> 17:15.826
<i>I literally just put the edge</i>
<i>straight into it</i>

17:15.826 --> 17:17.578
<i>and dig in.</i>

17:17.578 --> 17:19.580
<i>- The main thing about</i>
<i>what Cody has to deal with</i>

17:19.580 --> 17:22.208
is where that crack is.
It's definitely the spot

17:22.208 --> 17:23.542
that when you are hitting
something,

17:23.542 --> 17:24.627
there's pressure on that.

17:24.627 --> 17:26.587
It could rise and snap it off.

17:26.587 --> 17:29.298
<i>- The crack is coming out</i>
<i>and it's a massive relief.</i>

17:29.298 --> 17:30.967
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:30.967 --> 17:32.843
<i>- My biggest concern</i>
<i>going into round two</i>

17:32.843 --> 17:35.012
<i>is definitely that gut hook</i>
<i>and getting it sharp.</i>

17:35.012 --> 17:36.722
<i>You can't go on a belt sander</i>

17:36.722 --> 17:38.266
<i>and sharpen it like</i>
<i>a regular blade.</i>

17:38.266 --> 17:39.475
You have to really
just get in there

17:39.475 --> 17:41.185
and work it with your hand.

17:41.185 --> 17:43.437
<i>I'm struggling getting</i>
<i>the sandpaper up.</i>

17:43.437 --> 17:44.855
It's actually frustrating me

17:44.855 --> 17:46.440
that I can't get it
up in there.

17:46.440 --> 17:48.025
<i>I'm gonna use a dremel</i>

17:48.025 --> 17:49.694
<i>with a small, small</i>
<i>contact wheel</i>

17:49.694 --> 17:51.445
<i>and just kind of bring it</i>
<i>on the edges</i>

17:51.445 --> 17:53.531
<i>and make a sharp point</i>
<i>in the gut hook.</i>

17:53.531 --> 17:56.951
- Is the best way to sharpen
a gut hook area?

17:56.951 --> 17:58.786
- Nah, not if your gut hook
is hard.

17:58.786 --> 18:01.122
- He was working with
a fine sandpaper

18:01.122 --> 18:02.456
and a rod earlier.

18:02.456 --> 18:04.250
Second-guessing can be
a bad thing.

18:04.250 --> 18:06.627
<i>- At this point I know it's</i>
<i>not as sharp as my edge,</i>

18:06.627 --> 18:08.212
<i>but it feels fairly sharp.</i>

18:08.212 --> 18:09.964
It's definitely centered well
in the blade,

18:09.964 --> 18:11.674
<i>so it should be able to cut.</i>

18:11.674 --> 18:13.551
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:13.551 --> 18:16.554
<i>- For a competition like this,</i>
<i>I choose two scales</i>

18:16.554 --> 18:17.930
<i>of ironwood.</i>

18:17.930 --> 18:19.265
I mean, it has iron
in the name.

18:19.265 --> 18:21.142
Come on, it's gotta be good.

18:21.142 --> 18:22.685
<i>To get a good,</i>
<i>solid hold on it</i>

18:22.685 --> 18:24.353
<i>so it'll last through</i>
<i>the testing,</i>

18:24.353 --> 18:26.022
<i>you need really good contact</i>

18:26.022 --> 18:28.566
<i>with the glue</i>
<i>and the handle scales.</i>

18:28.566 --> 18:30.401
This stuff is just setting up
faster

18:30.401 --> 18:32.278
than I ever believed it could.

18:32.278 --> 18:33.821
- Mike's having
a little trouble.

18:33.821 --> 18:35.823
It is warm in here today
and that does actually

18:35.823 --> 18:37.742
speed up the curing
of epoxy.

18:37.742 --> 18:39.368
<i>- You need really</i>
<i>good contact</i>

18:39.368 --> 18:41.203
<i>so it's durable through</i>
<i>the testing.</i>

18:41.203 --> 18:42.830
Especially that bone chop, man.

18:42.830 --> 18:44.707
<i>That's terrifying stuff.</i>

18:44.707 --> 18:46.125
- One hour has elapsed!

18:46.125 --> 18:47.918
You have two hours remaining

18:47.918 --> 18:49.795
to finish your work!

18:49.795 --> 18:51.589
<i>- The tang is very narrow.</i>

18:51.589 --> 18:53.424
<i>So my plan of attack is</i>
<i>to get a fairly large</i>

18:53.424 --> 18:55.843
<i>piece of wood so I can contour</i>
<i>that to a very good,</i>

18:55.843 --> 18:57.553
comfortable grip.
[metal screeches]

18:57.553 --> 18:59.472
<i>You can't force a drill bit</i>
<i>through a tang</i>

18:59.472 --> 19:00.806
<i>when you hear that sound.</i>

19:00.806 --> 19:02.516
You will either burn the tip

19:02.516 --> 19:03.934
or you will break the bit off.

19:03.934 --> 19:05.603
Hmm.

19:05.603 --> 19:07.396
<i>- The material's hard.</i>
<i>Turn the speed up</i>

19:07.396 --> 19:09.899
<i>on that drill bit</i>
<i>about double what it is now.</i>

19:09.899 --> 19:11.400
- If I move up a little bit?

19:11.400 --> 19:12.818
[metal screeching]

19:12.818 --> 19:14.820
Mother [bleep]!
Does it again.

19:14.820 --> 19:16.364
I hate that sound so much.

19:16.364 --> 19:18.324
- Once you get
40 seconds of the

19:18.324 --> 19:20.117
[imitates metal screeching]
sound...

19:20.117 --> 19:21.994
- Yep.
- That drill bit's done.

19:21.994 --> 19:23.871
<i>- I see the rotary tool</i>
<i>and I'm thinking</i>

19:23.871 --> 19:26.499
<i>a drill won't go through</i>
<i>maybe an abrasive will.</i>

19:26.499 --> 19:27.625
And it works.

19:27.625 --> 19:29.085
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:29.085 --> 19:30.503
<i>- I get my handle</i>
<i>dry-fitted up,</i>

19:30.503 --> 19:31.921
<i>make sure all</i>
<i>the pins line up</i>

19:31.921 --> 19:33.172
<i>and everything lines up</i>
<i>perfectly</i>

19:33.172 --> 19:34.340
<i>and everything looks good.</i>

19:34.340 --> 19:35.716
I mix up some epoxy

19:35.716 --> 19:37.259
and I start to assemble
my handle,

19:37.259 --> 19:39.720
<i>and I get the epoxy</i>
<i>on one scale</i>

19:39.720 --> 19:41.430
<i>and the pins don't line up.</i>

19:41.430 --> 19:43.307
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:43.307 --> 19:45.059
<i>I don't understand.</i>
<i>I just checked it.</i>

19:45.059 --> 19:47.019
<i>I don't understand why</i>
<i>it's not going through.</i>

19:47.019 --> 19:48.729
I have five-minute epoxy.
I don't have time to be

19:48.729 --> 19:50.898
messing around.
I'm trying and I'm trying

19:50.898 --> 19:52.942
<i>and I can't get this scale</i>
<i>to fit with these pins.</i>

19:52.942 --> 19:55.945
<i>Then I realize the scale</i>
<i>is on the wrong side.</i>

19:55.945 --> 19:57.405
<i>I just put it on</i>
<i>the other side</i>

19:57.405 --> 20:00.199
<i>and everything lines</i>
<i>up perfectly.</i>

20:00.199 --> 20:01.492
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:01.492 --> 20:02.993
Yeah. [laughs]

20:02.993 --> 20:04.412
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:04.412 --> 20:06.038
<i>- I wanna put</i>
<i>a lanyard hole in.</i>

20:06.038 --> 20:07.790
<i>Put a mosaic pin,</i>
<i>maybe set it apart</i>

20:07.790 --> 20:10.084
a little bit from
the competitors' knives.

20:10.084 --> 20:12.461
<i>So I add the red color</i>
<i>into the epoxy</i>

20:12.461 --> 20:15.589
<i>because our school colors</i>
<i>are red and black.</i>

20:15.589 --> 20:18.551
And I'm a teacher
so I want kids to know

20:18.551 --> 20:20.511
<i>that taking a risk is a-okay.</i>

20:20.511 --> 20:22.138
<i>That's what makes life</i>
<i>go around.</i>

20:22.138 --> 20:24.640
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:24.640 --> 20:26.267
<i>- So I'm working on</i>
<i>the final bevels</i>

20:26.267 --> 20:27.852
<i>before I really start</i>
<i>sharpening it.</i>

